1
00:00:00,570 --> 00:00:05,560
You’ve probably heard the word “pullback”
or “retracement” or “correction” quite

2
00:00:05,560 --> 00:00:08,970
frequently if you’re interested in trading
the financial markets.

3
00:00:08,970 --> 00:00:10,340
So, what is a pullback?

4
00:00:10,340 --> 00:00:15,320
A pullback in a market is a pretty easy concept
to define and understand.

5
00:00:15,320 --> 00:00:20,980
It’s a period when price retraces back on
a recent move, either up or down.

6
00:00:20,980 --> 00:00:25,220
It’s basically a reversal of a recent price
move.

7
00:00:25,220 --> 00:00:26,640
Why are pullbacks important?

8
00:00:26,640 --> 00:00:33,070
For a number of reasons: they are opportunities
to enter the market at a “better price”,

9
00:00:33,070 --> 00:00:37,660
they allow for optimal stop loss placement,
improved risk reward and more.

10
00:00:37,660 --> 00:00:43,199
A pullback entry is more conservative than
a “market entry” for example and is considered

11
00:00:43,199 --> 00:00:44,870
a “safer” entry type.

12
00:00:44,870 --> 00:00:50,449
Ultimately, the goal of a trader is obtain
the best entry price and manage risk as good

13
00:00:50,449 --> 00:00:56,440
as possible whilst also increasing returns
and the pullback entry is a tool that allows

14
00:00:56,440 --> 00:00:59,320
you to do all three of these things.

15
00:00:59,320 --> 00:01:06,100
So here is why pullback trading is very important:
First, when identified correctly, will offer

16
00:01:06,100 --> 00:01:11,390
you higher probability entries
The very nature of a pullback means that price

17
00:01:11,390 --> 00:01:17,159
is likely to continue moving in the direction
of the initial move when the retrace ends.

18
00:01:17,159 --> 00:01:23,010
Hence, if you see a strong price action signal
at a level following a retracement, it’s

19
00:01:23,010 --> 00:01:29,579
a high-probability entry because all signs
are pointing to price bouncing from that point.

20
00:01:29,579 --> 00:01:35,530
Now, it doesn’t always happen, but waiting
for a retrace to a level with a signal, is

21
00:01:35,530 --> 00:01:38,920
the highest-probability way you can trade.

22
00:01:38,920 --> 00:01:44,049
Markets rotate back to the “mean” or “average”
price over and over; this is clear by looking

23
00:01:44,049 --> 00:01:45,280
at any price chart.

24
00:01:45,280 --> 00:01:50,439
So, when you see this retrace happen, start
looking for an entry point there because it’s

25
00:01:50,439 --> 00:01:55,759
a much higher-probability entry point than
simply entering “at market” like most

26
00:01:55,759 --> 00:01:57,549
traders do.

27
00:01:57,549 --> 00:02:02,009
Second, it offers better risk rewards.

28
00:02:02,009 --> 00:02:06,451
Pullback entries theoretically allow you to
place a “smaller” stop losses on a trade

29
00:02:06,451 --> 00:02:09,630
because you’re entering closer to a key
level.

30
00:02:09,630 --> 00:02:14,220
So, if you choose to do so, you can place
a stop much closer.

31
00:02:14,220 --> 00:02:22,160
For example: a 100 pips stop and 200 pips
target can easily become a 50 pip stop and

32
00:02:22,160 --> 00:02:26,140
250 pip target on a retrace entry.

33
00:02:26,140 --> 00:02:31,390
Of course: you don’t need to place a smaller
stop loss, it’s optional, but the option

34
00:02:31,390 --> 00:02:34,100
is there on a pullback entry if you want it.

35
00:02:34,100 --> 00:02:39,830
And, at the same time, a pullback entry allows
more flexibility with your stop loss placement.

36
00:02:39,830 --> 00:02:45,450
Of course, there are some negative aspects
in what concerns waiting for a pullback.

37
00:02:45,450 --> 00:02:47,170
You will have less trades in general.

38
00:02:47,170 --> 00:02:52,510
A lot of the time, markets simply don’t
retrace enough to trigger the more conservative

39
00:02:52,510 --> 00:02:55,140
entry that comes with a pull back.

40
00:02:55,140 --> 00:02:59,440
Instead, they may just keep going with minimal
retracements.

41
00:02:59,440 --> 00:03:04,860
This means you will have less chances to trade
as compared to someone who isn’t primarily

42
00:03:04,860 --> 00:03:06,100
waiting for pullbacks.

43
00:03:06,100 --> 00:03:10,150
Also, you will have more missed trades.

44
00:03:10,150 --> 00:03:15,060
Some potential good trades will “get away”
when waiting for a retracement that doesn’t

45
00:03:15,060 --> 00:03:16,060
happen, for example.

46
00:03:16,060 --> 00:03:19,160
This can test your nerves and will annoy you
sometimes.

47
00:03:19,160 --> 00:03:24,970
But, missing out on trades is not the worst
thing in the world and it’s better to miss

48
00:03:24,970 --> 00:03:27,840
out on some trades than to over-trade.

49
00:03:27,840 --> 00:03:34,172
Now that you now the pros and cons of a pullback
approach, let’s take a look at some of the

50
00:03:34,172 --> 00:03:37,870
different pullback entry type, so that you
can get a clear look at what they might look

51
00:03:37,870 --> 00:03:38,870
like.

52
00:03:38,870 --> 00:03:39,870
1.

53
00:03:39,870 --> 00:03:42,480
Pullback entry without any price action signal

54
00:03:42,480 --> 00:03:49,410
In this chart, you can see price pulled back
to the key horizontal level shown in the chart.

55
00:03:49,410 --> 00:03:55,590
There was no obvious price action signal here
but we can see price quickly sold-off from

56
00:03:55,590 --> 00:03:59,790
that level after just barely pushing above
it.

57
00:03:59,790 --> 00:04:05,690
This provided a very high potential risk reward
scenario if you decided to enter on a “blind

58
00:04:05,690 --> 00:04:08,950
entry” at that level with a tight stop loss.

59
00:04:08,950 --> 00:04:12,190
That’s the most aggressive entry.

60
00:04:12,190 --> 00:04:18,620
As soon as the price hits an important level,
you sell or buy at market immediately.

61
00:04:18,620 --> 00:04:24,100
You do not wait to confirm your buy or sell
signals with reversal candlesticks or signals

62
00:04:24,100 --> 00:04:26,390
from indicator.

63
00:04:26,390 --> 00:04:29,640
You just immediately buy or sell at market.

64
00:04:29,640 --> 00:04:35,940
If price hits the key level and bounces back,
you make money, if not, you lose.

65
00:04:35,940 --> 00:04:39,220
It’s that simple.

66
00:04:39,220 --> 00:04:41,760
2.

67
00:04:41,760 --> 00:04:48,790
Pullback to key level with price action confirmation
A more conservative trading strategy is to

68
00:04:48,790 --> 00:04:53,840
wait for price to retrace back up or down
to an existing key level on the daily chart

69
00:04:53,840 --> 00:04:58,370
time frame, then watch for an obvious price
action signal to form there.

70
00:04:58,370 --> 00:05:01,630
This is one of the highest-probability ways
to trade.

71
00:05:01,630 --> 00:05:06,530
A way to look for confirmation when using
pullbacks would be to look at Japanese candlestick

72
00:05:06,530 --> 00:05:12,350
formations because these tend to be reliable
signals of a reversal in price action.

73
00:05:12,350 --> 00:05:19,500
In particular, on this chart an engulfing
pattern forming right on key level could be

74
00:05:19,500 --> 00:05:22,630
a sign that price is ready to turn.

75
00:05:22,630 --> 00:05:28,020
For additional confirmation, you can apply
technical indicators such as stochastic or

76
00:05:28,020 --> 00:05:32,870
MACD to determine if it’s a good time to
enter a trade or not.

77
00:05:32,870 --> 00:05:38,070
Take note though that using too many technical
indicators doesn’t necessarily improve their

78
00:05:38,070 --> 00:05:39,070
reliability.

79
00:05:39,070 --> 00:05:45,810
In fact, too much indicators might lead to
an extremely cautious trading strategy that

80
00:05:45,810 --> 00:05:50,410
misses out on several valid trade signals.

81
00:05:50,410 --> 00:05:52,740
3.

82
00:05:52,740 --> 00:05:57,400
Pullback to a moving average
Markets have a tendency to retrace to the

83
00:05:57,400 --> 00:06:03,700
mean or average price, which you can see by
putting a moving average on your charts.

84
00:06:03,700 --> 00:06:08,960
Moving averages are useful for identifying
and confirming support and resistance levels.

85
00:06:08,960 --> 00:06:14,400
Most S/R levels, like market highs and lows,
pivot points, round numbers etc.

86
00:06:14,400 --> 00:06:16,060
Are static levels.

87
00:06:16,060 --> 00:06:21,370
Moving averages offer dynamic zones of support
and resistance because are changing depending

88
00:06:21,370 --> 00:06:23,830
on recent price action.

89
00:06:23,830 --> 00:06:31,889
On this daily chart we added a 20 EMA, a short-term
moving average to identify the trend.

90
00:06:31,889 --> 00:06:38,800
A simple EMA could be considered as a dynamic
area of support or resistance but also the

91
00:06:38,800 --> 00:06:44,090
area between two exponential moving averages
could also be considered as a dynamic area

92
00:06:44,090 --> 00:06:46,510
of support or resistance.

93
00:06:46,510 --> 00:06:52,610
When price retraces back to this area you
should watch closely for price action signals

94
00:06:52,610 --> 00:06:59,389
forming there to get a high-probability entry
and get in on a trending market.

95
00:06:59,389 --> 00:07:05,081
Using candlestick patterns with a moving average
helps to clarify the trend.

96
00:07:05,081 --> 00:07:08,600
It also helps you to evaluate the pullback
pattern better.

97
00:07:08,600 --> 00:07:14,260
Hence, combining candlestick patterns with
a moving average is a simple yet effective

98
00:07:14,260 --> 00:07:17,430
approach for trading pullbacks.

99
00:07:17,430 --> 00:07:19,990
This is EUR/JPY on the daily chart.

100
00:07:19,990 --> 00:07:28,960
We have a pin bar right on the 20-period EMA,
a high probability pullback trade.

101
00:07:28,960 --> 00:07:36,080
So, start paying attention to price action
patterns around moving averages.

102
00:07:36,080 --> 00:07:38,520
4.

103
00:07:38,520 --> 00:07:45,020
Pullbacks to the 50% - 61.8% Fibonacci area
Price has a tendency to retrace approximately

104
00:07:45,020 --> 00:07:48,090
50% of any major move and often times even
short-term moves.

105
00:07:48,090 --> 00:07:53,840
This is a well-documented phenomenon and if
you look at any chart you can see it happens,

106
00:07:53,840 --> 00:07:54,889
a lot.

107
00:07:54,889 --> 00:08:01,450
Hence, you can watch for pull backs to these
50% areas as they will very often be high

108
00:08:01,450 --> 00:08:08,710
probability levels for price to move beyond,
and as a result, price moves back in the direction

109
00:08:08,710 --> 00:08:12,080
of the initial move from that 50% level.

110
00:08:12,080 --> 00:08:17,550
It doesn’t happen every time of course,
but it happens often enough to make it a critical

111
00:08:17,550 --> 00:08:20,340
tool in your pullback trading tool box.

112
00:08:20,340 --> 00:08:27,150
I prefer to pay an extra attention to the
50%-61.8% fib area of a move, and look to

113
00:08:27,150 --> 00:08:29,080
trade entries.

114
00:08:29,080 --> 00:08:33,550
This chart shows the 4hour activity on the
pound dollar.

115
00:08:33,550 --> 00:08:37,940
This is the first strong upswing after a downwards
move.

116
00:08:37,940 --> 00:08:41,479
We drew the 50% and 61.8% retracement levels
of the bullish thrust.

117
00:08:41,479 --> 00:08:42,700
The area between them is the retracement zone.

118
00:08:42,700 --> 00:08:47,460
This sharp retracement down found support
at the retracement zone.

119
00:08:47,460 --> 00:08:51,920
The candlesticks that followed confirmed the
bullish pressure.

120
00:08:51,920 --> 00:08:58,060
As you can see we had 2 pullbacks, unable
to break below the 50% and 61.8% retracement

121
00:08:58,060 --> 00:08:59,830
area.

122
00:08:59,830 --> 00:09:04,920
You can use trend line breakouts for your
pullback entry, or search for obvious candlestick

123
00:09:04,920 --> 00:09:12,180
patterns, or even entries based on oscillators
or indicators.

124
00:09:12,180 --> 00:09:16,680
Trading pullbacks in a trending market is
one of the most efficient trading strategies

125
00:09:16,680 --> 00:09:17,680
out there.

126
00:09:17,680 --> 00:09:22,610
The beauty of a pullback trading system is
that you enter the market or place your first

127
00:09:22,610 --> 00:09:26,520
trade only after confirming which way the
market is going.

128
00:09:26,520 --> 00:09:32,089
Doing this is going to help you eliminate
entering the market with a false signal.

129
00:09:32,089 --> 00:09:38,660
Since most markets remain within a range bound
or consolidation phase most of the time, and

130
00:09:38,660 --> 00:09:44,420
the market trends only about 20 to 30 percent
of the time, finding an established trend

131
00:09:44,420 --> 00:09:47,630
to trade pullbacks can be a challenging task.

132
00:09:47,630 --> 00:09:52,830
As a trader when you are trying to apply a
pullback strategy, you need to act like a

133
00:09:52,830 --> 00:09:53,830
sniper.

134
00:09:53,830 --> 00:09:57,390
You need to wait and have discipline and patience
before pulling the trigger.

135
00:09:57,390 --> 00:10:02,560
Also, very important, you need to make sure
that you have identified the correct turning

136
00:10:02,560 --> 00:10:05,590
point, where the pullback move is likely to
end.

137
00:10:05,590 --> 00:10:11,090
It’s your job to find a way to generate
a high probability pullback signal where the

138
00:10:11,090 --> 00:10:13,650
price is likely to resume the prevailing trend.

139
00:10:13,650 --> 00:10:19,000
If you can successfully do this, you can buy
low during an uptrend and sell high during

140
00:10:19,000 --> 00:10:24,110
a downtrend, and this can only bring profits
in the long run.

141
00:10:24,110 --> 00:10:28,480
If you learned something new and found value,
don’t forget to subscribe, click the bell

142
00:10:28,480 --> 00:10:34,020
icon so you’ll be notified each time we
